# Rust build artefacts
/target/
**/target/

# Cargo.lock IS committed.
#
# This workspace produces a binary (the evo steward); reproducible builds
# require the lockfile to be under version control so every developer,
# every CI run, and every release build resolves to the same dependency
# graph. Library crates (no binaries) conventionally omit the lockfile;
# workspaces that ship any binary include it. See:
#   https://doc.rust-lang.org/cargo/faq.html#why-have-cargolock-in-version-control

# Editor and OS junk
.DS_Store
Thumbs.db
*.swp
*.swo
*~
.idea/
.vscode/
*.iml

# Environment and local config
.env
.env.local

# Acceptance harness — machine-specific overlays (host, ssh user,
# ssh key path). The committed target descriptors carry public-shape
# capabilities only; connection details live in a sibling
# `<target>.local.toml` overlay loaded at runtime. Never commit.
acceptance/targets/*.local.toml

# Generated documentation
/book/
/docs/_build/

# Signing keys - never commit
*.key
*.pem
!docs/**/*.pem.example
# Public halves of release-signing and trust-root keys live under
# keys/ and ARE committed: an operator verifying a fetched
# artefact needs the public key in the source clone. Names follow
# the convention <role>-public.pem so the rule is purely
# suffix-based.
!keys/*-public.pem

# Archived artefacts
.archive/

# AI tooling — never committed.
#
# This block excludes per-machine settings, project memories,
# caches, and rule files for every coding-assistant tool. The
# concern is two-fold: (1) per-user / per-machine settings
# (allowlists, model preferences, auth state) leaking into the
# public repo, and (2) project-memory files containing context
# that does not belong in the public source tree. JetBrains AI
# assistant subdirectories are already covered by the `.idea/`
# rule above. When in doubt, keep AI-tool artefacts out of this
# repo.
.claude/
CLAUDE.md
CLAUDE.local.md
.cursor/
.cursorrules
.cursorignore
.aider*
.aiderignore
.continue/
.windsurf/
.windsurfrules
.codeium/
.zed/
.junie/
# GitHub Copilot project-instructions file lives under .github/
# (which is otherwise CI configuration that IS committed); name
# it explicitly so it shares this section's discipline.
.github/copilot-instructions.md

# Local-only directory; never committed. The trailing slash
# excludes the directory and everything below it without
# affecting an unrelated file that might share the basename.
.evo-internal/
